AgOCN.name: Silver fulminate
AgOCN.desc: Silver fulminate is the highly explosive silver salt of fulminic acid. Silver fulminate is a primary explosive, but has limited use as such due to its extreme sensitivity to impact, heat, pressure and electricity.

Ag2S.name: Silver sulfide
Ag2S.desc: Silver sulfide is the sulfide of silver. It is useful as a photosensitizer in photography.
Ag2S.solblty: Soluble in aq. HCN, aq. citric acid with KNO3. Insoluble in acids, alkalies, aqueous ammoniums

AgBr.name: Silver bromide
AgBr.desc: Silver bromide, a soft, pale-yellow, water-insoluble salt well known for its unusual sensitivity to light. This property has allowed silver halides to become the basis of modern photographic materials.
AgBr.solblty: Insoluble in alcohol, most acids. sparingly soluble in ammonia soluble in alkali cyanide solutions
AgBr.genEq:
AgBr is typically prepared by the reaction of silver nitrate with an alkali bromide, typically potassium bromide.

AgNO3(aq) + KBr(aq) → AgBr(s)+ KNO3(aq)

AgCl.name: Silver chloride
AgCl.desc: Silver chloride is a chemical compound with the chemical formula AgCl. This white crystalline solid is well known for its low solblty in water.
AgCl.solblty:
soluble in NH3, conc. HCl, conc. H2SO4, alkali cyanide, NH4CO3?, KBr, Na2S2O3.
Insoluble in alcohol, dilute acids.

AgI.name: Silver iodide
AgI.desc: Silver iodide is an inorganic compound with the formula AgI. The compound is a bright yellow solid, but samples almost always contain impurities of metallic silver that give a gray coloration. The silver contamination arises because AgI is highly photosensitive.
AgI.genEq:
Silver iodide is prepared by reaction of an iodide solution (e.g., potassium iodide) with a solution of silver ions (e.g., silver nitrate). A yellowish solid quickly precipitates.
AgNO3 + KI → AgI + KNO3

AgN3.name: Silver azide
AgN3.desc: Silver azide is the chemical compound with the formula AgN₃. This colorless solid is a well-known explosive.
AgN3.genEq:
Silver azide can be prepared by treating an aqueous solution of silver nitrate with sodium azide.[2] The silver azide precipitates as a white solid, leaving sodium nitrate in solution.
AgNO3 (aq) + NaN3 (aq) → AgN3 (s) + NaNO3 (aq)

AgO.name: Silver(I,III) oxide
AgO.otherName: Silver peroxide, Argentic oxide, Silver suboxide, Divasil
AgO.desc: Silver(I, III) oxide is the inorganic compound with the formula Ag<sub>4</sub>O<sub>4</sub>. It is a component of silver oxide-zinc alkaline batteries. It can be prepared by the slow addition of a silver(I) salt to a persulfate solution e.g. AgNO<sub>3</sub> to a Na<sub>2</sub>S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>8</sub> solution.
AgO.genEq: In 1.5 liters of aqueous solution containing 150 grams of sodium hydroxide, 65 grams of silver powder are suspended with continuous stirring. The silver powder has a density of approximately 1.6 grams per cubic centimeter. Its grain size distribution is: 52% under 10 microns; 33% 10 microns to 30 microns, 15% above 30 microns.  The liquid is then heated to about 85° C. Upon reaching this temperature, a total of 200 grams of potassium peroxidisulfate (K2S2O8) in portions of about 40 grams each is added at intervals of, for example, 1 hour. After addition of the final portion of oxidant, stirring is continued for 3 hours. The product is then filtered, washed to free it of alkali substances, dried at a temperature of approximately 80° C and reduced to particle form.

Al2O3.name: Aluminium oxide
Al2O3.genEq:
Corundum is the most common naturally occurring crystalline form of aluminium oxide. Rubies and sapphires are gem-quality forms of corundum, which owe their characteristic colors to trace impurities. Rubies are given their characteristic deep red color and their laser qualities by traces of chromium. Sapphires come in different colors given by various other impurities, such as iron and titanium.
Aluminium Oxide can also be prepared by Trimethylaluminum Al(CH3)3 and H2O:
2 Al(CH3)3 + 3 H2O → Al2O3 + 6 CH4
H2O in the above reaction was subsequently replaced by ozone (O3) as the active oxidant and the following reaction took place.
2 Al(CH3)3 + O3 → Al2O3 + 3 C2H6
